<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-767-328  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 767 328.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  July 9 1990 v219 n2 p19(3).andM;ne</JOURNAL><TITLE>The power of CO-LANs: new technology breathes life into CO-LANs,enabling telephone companies to meet a variety of customer dataneeds. (central office-local area networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hart, Nancy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Central office-local area networks (CO-LANs) are data servicesthat share existing phone lines with voice.andP;  Current demand forlow-cost data services is enormous, and CO-LANs provide telephonecompanies with a way to meet this demand.andP;  Until recently, CO-LANshad captured the interest neither of phone companies nor of endusers, but advances in transmission and switching equipment meanthat central office-local area networks (CO-LANs) are now easierto use and are more functional.andP;  Time is a factor for CO-LANimplementation because while telcos develop integrated servicesdigital network (ISDN) services, customers are setting up theirown networks, and once customers establish their own networks, thechances that they will return to the public network are remote.andO;CO-LANs do not compete with ISDN but complement it, providing ISDNfunctionality today while supplying a migration path to true ISDNfor the future.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telephone systemsLocal Area NetworksTelephone companiesCommunications EquipmentISDN.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   CO-LAN connectivity options. (chart)Transmission technologies. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>